We start solving the problem by looking at how we can be able to get the only term to go away and get from $(x-1)(x+2)(x-3)$. This means that we only need to find the values of $A$, $B$, and $C$ first. By doing that, we can go back to our example of $A(x-2)(x-3)+B(x-1)(x-3)+C(x-1)(x-2)=1$, where $x$ can equal $1$, $-2$, and $3$.
Plug in $x=3$, we get:
